Breast Cancer Dataset¶

Classify tumors into malignant (cancerous) or benign(non-cancerous) using unsupervised clustering methods¶

Using this dataset I want to identify malginant tumors while applying dimentionality reduction and clustering methods

dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nancyalaswad90/breast-cancer-dataset

The dataset is a collection of measurements of cell nuclei of different biopsies (needle aspirate) done on malignant and beneign tumors. The measured features are:

a) radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)

b) texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)

c) perimeter

d) area

e) smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)

f) compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)

g) concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)

h) concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)

i) symmetry

j) fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

EDA¶

  • Overview of the data
  • Target class balance
  • Correlation between the features
  • Uniformity of the data

def plot_explained_variance(pca):
    # This function graphs the accumulated explained variance ratio for a fitted PCA object.
    acc = [*accumulate(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(50, 20))
    ax.stackplot(range(pca.n_components_), acc)
    ax.scatter(range(pca.n_components_), acc, color='black')
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
    ax.set_xlim(0, pca.n_components_-1)
    ax.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=36)
    ax.set_xlabel('N Components', fontsize=48)
    ax.set_ylabel('Accumulated explained variance', fontsize=48)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Testing out different models¶

First a simple logistic regression¶

from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
from scipy.optimize import linear_sum_assignment
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.cluster import MeanShift, estimate_bandwidth
In [ ]:
def map_clusters(y_true, y_pred):
    """Map cluster labels to match true labels."""
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    row_ind, col_ind = linear_sum_assignment(-cm)  # maximize total match
    label_map = dict(zip(col_ind, row_ind))

    return np.vectorize(label_map.get)(y_pred)

def get_avg_score(n, estimator=None):
    sss = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=5, random_state=80, test_size=0.1)

    if estimator==None:
        estimator = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear')
    pipe = [
        ('log1p', FunctionTransformer(np.log1p)),
        ('pca', PCA(n_components=0.99)),
        ('estimator', estimator)
    ]
    pipe = Pipeline(pipe)
    acc_scores = []
    prec_scores = []
    rec_scores = []

    for train_index, test_index in sss.split(X, y):
        X_train, X_test = X.loc[train_index], X.loc[test_index]
        y_train, y_test = y.loc[train_index], y.loc[test_index]
        pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_hat = pipe.predict(X_test)

        # If unsupervised (e.g., KMeans), map clusters to class labels
        if isinstance(pipe['estimator'], (KMeans, GaussianMixture, MeanShift)):
            y_hat = map_clusters(y_test, y_hat)

            
        acc_scores.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_hat))
        prec_scores.append(precision_score(y_test, y_hat))
        rec_scores.append(recall_score(y_test, y_hat))

        

    print(f'Mean accuracy: {np.mean(acc_scores)}')
    print(f'Mean precision: {np.mean(prec_scores)}')
    print(f'Mean recall: {np.mean(rec_scores)}')
    return acc_scores, prec_scores, rec_scores

acc_scores, prec_scores, rec_scores = get_avg_score(3)

Mean accuracy: 0.968421052631579
Mean precision: 0.9722943722943723
Mean recall: 0.9428571428571428

Gaussian Mixture¶

In [ ]:
acc_scores_gaus, prec_scores_gaus, rec_scores_gaus = get_avg_score(3, GaussianMixture(n_components=2, random_state=42))

Mean accuracy: 0.9192982456140351
Mean precision: 0.8365797101449275
Mean recall: 0.9714285714285713

Conclusion¶

Even though the accuracy and precision are better in the linear model and the K-Means we would chose the Gaussian Mixture model. When dealing with ML applications in the medical field we want to aim for models with high recall. This is because we are more interested in finding all of the cancerous tumors than getting false positives. Of course we also aim to have a high precision to avoid unnecessary stress/treatment.
